snippet.textDisplay: hi, loved the video! I can raccomand Vincotto as a spred, it’s an italian spread made with wine in southern Italy, it has the consistency of caramel and is used mainly on pastry or in biscuit batter, it has quite a strange flavor and as a kid I used to hate it, but now I really love it. snippet.textDisplay:
Aah Kaya (I would like to believe they remove the first y in Nyonya to get Nonya for pronunciation sake)
1.Toast or steamed bread with kaya and butter
2. Filling for desserts also found in Malaysian traditional desserts (kuih)
3. Pancake or waffle spreads
4. Alkaline water rice dumpling dipped in Kaya during dumpling or dragon boat festival
5. Kaya balls ( round buns similarly cooked like Takayuki filled with kaya)
6. Kaya flavour ice cream
7. Kaya Mille crepe
8. Etc etc etc!

snippet.textDisplay:
Easy, kind of messy pie (needs refrigeration) is: jelly jam banana pie - biscuit pie shell, spread a thin layer of strawberry jam over the cooled shell, sliced banana layer, mostly set lemon jelly smothered over the top (makes up most of the pie; if you put it in liquid it'll make the crust soggy), and then top it with whipped cream to serve. Easy to make, tastes great!



I'm gonna be looking into sauces and dressings made with jams and marmalades after watching this. Personally, I've always found Jam a bit too sweet to be the dominant thing you have on toast. I'll have it as a treat, though: orange marmalade or apricot jam with cheese on toast; strawberry or raspberry on the side of a plate for dipping a croissant into; jam between sponge layers to jazz up a cream cake; spoonful of jam in plain unsweetened yoghurt to make whatever flavour you're in the mood for, less obnoxiously sweet than shop bought flavoured yoghurt. Also works in ice-cream if you're really after something sweet.
